description.narrative: Evidence-based health system strengthening tools and strategies are in place for delivery of quality care for all., which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, more children and women access and utilize quality health services

description.narrative: More newborns, children, adolescents, and women accessed and utilised quality health services through UNICEF support – over 9,600 small and sick newborns received quality in-patient care in 5 regions and nearly 90% of low-birth-weight babies received kangaroo mother care. Over one million children under one year received a third dose of DTP, almost 700 HIV exposed children received EID services and 75% of children infected received treatment and follow up care. About 140,000 pregnant adolescents identified and enrolled in the Safety Net Programme and over 4,700 women empowered with information, education and counselling to demand quality MNCH services.;; | Status:On-track | As-of Date:13/01/2022
